metadata.name: Across Paper Stones #230
metadata.description:
Wherever you want to go, you'll find a path to take you there.

Each tile is made up of two deformed rectangles. One is drawn with a drifting, fragmented outline.

Over thirty color palettes are shuffled together on each output, helping form slight edges between groups.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.

metadata.name: Urban Building: Where Are We Going? #87
metadata.description:
This is a building generation made by pure code.

Urbanization at the almost everywhere in the world has stepped into an accelerating phase in last century. Buildings bring magnificent achievements and represent the human power over nature. But, following these tall and crowd buildings one by one, where are we going?

In this work, I generate different types of building with a special viewpoint, which represent different concepts of states we are going to. Hope you enjoy these varieties and coincidences.

Variables:
- 4 modes
- 4 environments
- 3 orbs
- 3 building density
- 3 building structures

Please be patient with drawing process.

metadata.name: matrix #80
metadata.description:
A minimalist raining code sequence based on your unique hash.
The animation is generated by this code:

f=n=>{for(t++,o=i="",w=28;
i<387;o+=h[i++].fontcolor(
g<9&&g>0?c[0|g%9]:0)+(i%w?
"":"\n"))g=(i/w-t/s[i%w]+w
*t+100)%w;pre.innerHTML=o}

Variables:

- Matrix: Hash, Source Code, Binary
- Colors: Green, Cyan, Blue, Purple, Yellow, White 

The default is using your fxhash as an output and a green / white color scheme. Rare variations are created for 50% of the editions.

metadata.name: Subatomic Compositions #395
metadata.description:
My love of physics predates my love for generative systems. This piece explores the compositional beauty that can arise from particle collisions in the subatomic space. The aesthetic is based on bubble chamber photography: the paths of particles are traced and photographed as they split and collide.

The primary particle travels at extreme speeds, looping around until it collides with another particle. The resulting explosion is traced out and interesting events are highlighted. Some of the particles shoot off at incredible velocity, and others spiral tighter and tighter until they blink out of existence.

This is a study in composition.
